	<!-- 
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
   Schema: Requirement_identification_and_version_arm  Entity: Requirement  
   <express_ref linkend="requirement_identification_and_version:arm:Requirement_identification_and_version_arm.Requirement"/>
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++ 
  -->
	<ext_description linkend="Requirement_identification_and_version_arm.Requirement">

    A <b>Requirement</b> is a type of 
   <express_ref linkend="product_identification:arm:Product_identification_arm.Product"/>
   that is used to uniquely identify a requirement.

		<note number="1">
   The term "requirement" is used here in the sense that term is used in
   systems engineering and similar industrial domains. 
 </note>
		<note number="2">
   There may be many versions of a requirement <express_ref linkend="requirement_identification_and_version:arm:Requirement_identification_and_version_arm.Requirement_version"/>

). There
   may also be more than  one domain-specific view of a given
   <express_ref linkend="requirement_identification_and_version:arm:Requirement_identification_and_version_arm.Requirement_version"/>

 (using the<express_ref linkend="requirement_view_definition:arm:Requirement_view_definition_arm.Requirement_view_definition"/>  entity).  
   The requirement entity is simply a placeholder for holding a unique requirement. Most associations 
   and properties are defined at the <express_ref linkend="requirement_view_definition:arm:Requirement_view_definition_arm.Requirement_view_definition"/>  level - i.e. in the context of a domain.
 </note>
		<example>
   A requirement may be identified as "NOx emissions requirement", and uniquely identified as "Req2".
 </example>
		<note number="3">
   Systems engineering tools and organizations may use differing identification mechanisms. Multiple 
   identifiers may be assigned to a requirement using the <express_ref linkend="alias_identification:arm:Alias_identification_arm.Alias_identification"/> entity.
 </note>
	</ext_description>
	<!-- 
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
   Schema: Requirement_identification_and_version_arm  Entity: Requirement_version  
   <express_ref linkend="requirement_identification_and_version:arm:Requirement_identification_and_version_arm.Requirement_version"/>
  ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++ 
  -->
	<ext_description linkend="Requirement_identification_and_version_arm.Requirement_version">

    A <b>Requirement_version</b> is a type of 
  <express_ref linkend="product_version:arm:Product_version_arm.Product_version"/>
  that identifies a particular version of a requirement.

		<note>
  This entity is used to record different versions of a requirement. In
  this case, the word "version" implies "revision"  
  - i.e. a particular	release of a requirement.
</note>
		<example>
  A given requirement might have versions 1.0, 1.1, 1.2 and 2.0.
</example>
	</ext_description>
